class Solution {
    private void helper(int index,int currentSum, int[] nums, List<Integer> result ){
        if(index==nums.length){
            result.add(currentSum);
            return;
        }
        helper(index+1, currentSum+nums[index], nums, result);
        helper(index+1, currentSum, nums, result);
    }
    public List<Integer> subsetSums(int[] nums) {
        //your code goes here
        List<Integer> result = new ArrayList<>();
        helper(0,0,nums,result);
        Collections.sort(result);
        return result;
    }
}

Time Complexity: O(2^n),Each element has two choices: include or exclude, leading to 2n subsets. We directly compute sums without iterating over subsets, so complexity is O(2n). Sorting the sums adds O(2n log(2n)), making the total O(2n log(2n)).

Space Complexity: O(2^n),The result array holds all subset sums, requiring O(2n) space. Recursion uses an additional O(n) stack space due to function calls, so total auxiliary space is O(2n + n).
